Problem Definition

Film production is a high-risk investment activity, where large financial commitments are made under significant uncertainty about audience preferences and market response. Producers must decide on critical factors such as genre, runtime, and content style without clear, data-backed evidence of what drives movie success.

Despite the availability of public platforms like IMDb that capture audience ratings and popularity metrics, these signals are often conflictingsome movies receive high ratings but limited popularity, while others attract massive audiences despite average ratings. This ambiguity makes it difficult for producers to make informed investment decisions.

This project aims to leverage IMDb data to identify patterns and relationships between movie characteristics and audience response, thereby reducing uncertainty in production planning.

Business Problem Statement

Vamshi,a movie producer with a limited production budget, wants to invest in his next film while maximizing the probability of success and minimizing financial risk.

However, he faces multiple uncertainties:

  • Which movie genres are more likely to be well-received by audiences
  • What movie duration provides the best balance between engagement and satisfaction
  • Whether traditional storytelling styles still resonate with modern audiences
  • Whether high IMDb ratings reliably translate into high audience popularity

The absence of clear, data-driven guidance makes these decisions speculative and increases the likelihood of investment failure.

Business Questions

Genre Preference : Which movie genres are most consistently associated with higher audience ratings?

Runtime Optimization : What movie duration range yields the most stable and favorable audience response?

Popularity vs Quality : Is there a strong relationship between IMDb ratings and movie popularity (votes)?

Audience Behavior : Do highly rated movies always attract high audience engagement?

Strategic Risk : Which combination of movie attributes offers a safer investment choice for producers with budget constraints?

Project Objectives

  • To collect and construct a structured IMDb movie dataset

by scraping publicly available movie information, including ratings, vote counts, genres, runtime, and release year.

  • To perform data cleaning and preprocessing

to ensure consistency, eliminate missing values, and prepare the dataset for reliable analysis.

  • To analyze genre-wise audience acceptance

by examining rating distributions and identifying genres that consistently receive higher audience appreciation.

  • To study the relationship between movie ratings and popularity

using statistical measures and hypothesis testing to determine whether higher ratings correspond to greater audience engagement.

  • To examine runtime and decade-wise trends

in order to understand how audience preferences have evolved over time and to identify optimal movie duration ranges.

  • To apply hypothesis testing techniques

to statistically validate key relationships between movie attributes such as genre, runtime, popularity, and ratings.

  • To derive actionable, data-driven insights

that can support movie producers in selecting safer, high-potential movie concepts under budget constraints.

HYPOTHESIS 1: Directors Success Depends on Genre

Does a director tend to achieve higher success in certain genres

Hypotheses
  • H: A directors movie success is independent of genre.
  • H: A directors movie success is associated with genre
Statistical Test

Chi-Square Test

    lambda x: "Successful" if x >= 7.5 else "Not Successful")

In[46]:
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency

chi2, p_value, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)

print("Chi-square statistic:", chi2)
print("p-value:", p_value)

if p_value < 0.05:
    print("Reject H  Directors success depends on genre")
else:
    print("Fail to reject H  No strong genre-specific success")

Fail to reject H  No strong genre-specific success

HYPOTHESIS 2: Movie Runtime Category Influences IMDb Rating

Does the duration of a movie significantly influence audience ratings?

Hypotheses
  • H: Mean IMDb ratings are equal across different runtime categories
  • H: At least one runtime category has a significantly different mean IMDb rating.
Statistical Test

One-way ANOVA

In[47]:
from scipy.stats import f_oneway

runtime_groups = [
    df[df["runtime_bin"] == cat]["imdb_rating"]
    for cat in df["runtime_bin"].dropna().unique()
]

f_stat_2, p_value_2 = f_oneway(*runtime_groups)

print("Hypothesis 2: Runtime Category vs IMDb Rating")
print("F-statistic:", f_stat_2)
print("p-value:", p_value_2)

if p_value_2 < 0.05:
    print("Reject H  Ratings differ across runtime categories")
else:
    print("Fail to reject H  No significant difference in ratings")

Hypothesis 2: Runtime Category vs IMDb Rating
F-statistic: 9.568628777806259
p-value: 1.1579140223037115e-07
Reject H  Ratings differ across runtime categories

HYPOTHESIS 3: Movie Genre Influences IMDb Rating

Does Genre of a Movie impact on ratings

Drama-oriented genres appeared to have higher median ratings than action or comedy genres.

Hypotheses
  • H: Mean IMDb ratings are equal across all movie genres.
  • H: At least one genre has a significantly different mean IMDb rating.
Statistical Test

One-way ANOVA

In[48]:
from scipy.stats import f_oneway

genre_groups = [
    df_genre[df_genre["genre"] == g]["imdb_rating"]
    for g in df_genre["genre"].dropna().unique()
]

f_stat_3, p_value_3 = f_oneway(*genre_groups)

print("Hypothesis 3: Genre vs IMDb Rating")
print("F-statistic:", f_stat_3)
print("p-value:", p_value_3)

if p_value_3 < 0.05:
    print("Reject H  Ratings differ significantly across genres")
else:
    print("Fail to reject H  No significant genre-level difference")

Hypothesis 3: Genre vs IMDb Rating
F-statistic: 12.13238723882381
p-value: 2.1277439278346605e-42
Reject H  Ratings differ significantly across genres
